  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) is a marvel of modern engineering and international cooperation, serving as a habitable space laboratory where astronauts and researchers conduct scientific experiments in microgravity. Here's an overview of **how** and **when** the ISS was sent to space:\n\n### **When Was the ISS Launched?**\n\n- **Initial Launch:** The journey of the ISS began on **November 20, 1998**, with the launch of the first module, **Zarya** (\u201cSunrise\u201d in Russian). This module was launched aboard a Russian Proton rocket from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan.\n  \n- **Assembly Phase:** Following Zarya, the ISS assembly involved multiple launches of various modules and components over several years. Key milestones include:\n  - **Unity Module (Node 1):** Launched on **December 4, 1998**, aboard the U.S. Space Shuttle Endeavour during the STS-88 mission. This was the first U.S.-built component and acted as a connecting hub for other modules.\n  - **Zvezda Service Module:** Launched on **July 12, 2000**, using a Russian Proton rocket. It provided living quarters, life support, and essential systems.\n  - **Additional Modules:** Throughout the 2000s, various modules like Destiny (U.S. laboratory), Quest (airlock), Columbus (European laboratory), and Kibo (Japanese laboratory) were added through subsequent launches and Space Shuttle missions.\n  \n- **Completion of Major Assembly:** By **2011**, with the final Space Shuttle mission (Atlantis on STS-135), the core structure of the ISS was largely complete, although ongoing upgrades and maintenance continue to this day.\n\n### **How Was the ISS Sent to Space?**\n\n- **International Collaboration:** The ISS is a joint project involving five space agencies:\n  - **NASA** (United States)\n  - **Roscosmos** (Russia)\n  - **JAXA** (Japan)\n  - **ESA** (European Space Agency)\n  - **CSA** (Canadian Space Agency)\n  \n- **Launch Vehicles:** Various rockets were used to transport modules and components into low Earth orbit:\n  - **Russian Proton and Soyuz Rockets:** Primarily used for launching Russian modules and components.\n  - **NASA Space Shuttles:** From 1998 to 2011, the Space Shuttle fleet was crucial for launching large modules, conducting assembly tasks, and transporting astronauts.\n  \n- **Assembly in Orbit:** Once modules were in orbit, astronauts and cosmonauts performed spacewalks (extravehicular activities) to connect modules, install systems, and ensure structural integrity. This meticulous process transformed separate modules into a unified, functioning space station.\n\n- **Continuous Upgrades and Maintenance:** After the initial assembly, the ISS has been continuously serviced and upgraded by various spacecraft:\n  - **Space Shuttles (until 2011):** Facilitated major upgrades and repairs.\n  - **Russian Soyuz and Progress Vehicles:** Provide crew transport and cargo resupply.\n  - **Commercial Vehicles:** In recent years, companies like SpaceX (with Falcon 9 rockets and Crew Dragon/Cargo Dragon spacecraft) and Northrop Grumman (with Cygnus spacecraft) have played significant roles in resupply and crew transportation.\n\n### **Current Status and Future**\n\nAs of October 2023, the ISS continues to operate as a multinational research laboratory, hosting astronauts from around the world and conducting experiments across a wide range of scientific disciplines, including biology, physics, astronomy, and Earth science. Plans are underway to extend its operational life into the late 2020s or early 2030s, after which it may be succeeded by new space stations under development by NASA and international partners.\n\n### **Key Takeaways**\n\n- **Start Date:** First module launched in November 1998.\n- **International Effort:** Collaboration among NASA, Roscosmos, JAXA, ESA, and CSA.\n- **Multiple Launches:** Involved various rockets (Proton, Soyuz, Space Shuttles, Falcon 9) and numerous missions for assembly and maintenance.\n- **Ongoing Operations:** Continues to serve as a hub for scientific research and international cooperation in space.\n\nThe ISS stands as a testament to what humanity can achieve through collaboration, innovation, and dedication to exploring beyond our planet.",
